    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2722634533" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2722634533" />
    <a title="Noria" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/88976168-noria"><img alt="Noria" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1541504192p2/88976168.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2722634533?book_show_action=true">Feb 27, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Noria" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Noria" href="/user/show/88976168-noria">Noria</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/88976168-noria?shelf=enjoyed">enjoyed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/88976168-noria?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/88976168-noria?shelf=best-sci-fi-books">best-sci-fi-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2722634533" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12317289177771969740">I have so many thoughts, each one of them individual pieces that are trying to absorb all I have read and mix and match it to form a perfect whole; like I am my very own Ooloi creating a construct of all that these book made me feel. Spoiler alert: I am human and I can&apos;t. This book made me feel it all: anger, sadness, rage, resignation, numbness, fatigue, pain, despair and finally hope.<br/><br/>Set in a post-apocalyptic world where humans as expected have led to the destruction of the world due to our hi</span>
  <span id="freeText12317289177771969740" style="display:none">I have so many thoughts, each one of them individual pieces that are trying to absorb all I have read and mix and match it to form a perfect whole; like I am my very own Ooloi creating a construct of all that these book made me feel. Spoiler alert: I am human and I can't. This book made me feel it all: anger, sadness, rage, resignation, numbness, fatigue, pain, despair and finally hope.<br /><br />Set in a post-apocalyptic world where humans as expected have led to the destruction of the world due to our hierarchical nature (our desire to establish supremacy and use force in order to enforce power over one group; a grand posturing that more often than not leads to death and destruction) and our intelligence: a lethal combo that the Oankali saw and recognized and realized we had to weed out from our genes in order to guarantee our survival as a species. Lilith's Brood opened my eyes to the failings of humanity as I'd never considered it and this is one of the first alien invasion novel where I was mostly team aliens over mankind. I say mostly because I did have some problems with the aliens' sometimes not listening to the words of the humans because they could "read" what their body wanted (and they really could. The Oankali are purely biological and they read signals that humans have long learned to ignore). Although I could see that them reading those feelings were beneficial in the long term, it still irked me that they sometimes put what they wanted over what the humans said they wanted and I appreciated that even the humans who had accepted Oankali mates sometimes resented them for it. It made the story more believable for me.<br /><br />I also loved the progression of the story. We started with Lilith who was human and as such showed us this new alien life and her slow acclimatization to it was ours as well. Then we moved on to Akin's perspective, who was a human construct Oankali; looked more visibly human with alien traits and slowly became more alien even though internally he retained parts of his humanity. And then we finished with Jodahs whose metamorphosis into Ooloi went seamlessly that I had no idea when I started to see not just the book but the world around me with alien eyes. <br /><br />This is a book that makes you question who truly is the one to fear: humans with their guns and their propensity for violence towards what they don't understand and who thought they could take whatever they wanted because they felt fear; or the aliens who were offering peace and although they had a problem with consent (I kid you not, some of the scenes read rapey and I had a problem with that, tbt) still accepted differences and believed that difference was important to the survival of a life-form. <br /><br />It's a book I look forward to reading over and over again, although not any time soon because right now, I feel just like Jodahs did after Nikanj fed it with all the information it needed to become an adult Ooloi: bombarded with way too much information and needing years for everything to fully settle in, and that is how you know that a book is fucking amazing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12317289177771969740" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


