<div id="review_9014248" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/9014248" />
    <a title="Elise" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/616282-elise"><img alt="Elise" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1245861216p2/616282.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/9014248?book_show_action=true">Nov 12, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elise" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elise" href="/user/show/616282-elise">Elise</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/616282-elise?shelf=sci-fi-fantasy">sci-fi-fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer9014248" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12537562497213832220">Octavia Butler uses this book to explore what makes us human by taking humanity completely out of its known context and giving it a whole new one with fundamental restrictions and specifically chosen opportunities. This allows her to put humanity in high-relief, and I have to say a lot of what she says strikes a chord -- her definition of the Human Contradiction, for example, is spot-on. I think she does get a little bit heavy-handed -- I feel there&apos;s a little more gray scale to human behavior t</span>
  <span id="freeText12537562497213832220" style="display:none">Octavia Butler uses this book to explore what makes us human by taking humanity completely out of its known context and giving it a whole new one with fundamental restrictions and specifically chosen opportunities. This allows her to put humanity in high-relief, and I have to say a lot of what she says strikes a chord -- her definition of the Human Contradiction, for example, is spot-on. I think she does get a little bit heavy-handed -- I feel there's a little more gray scale to human behavior than perhaps she decided to paint on -- but all in all it's an amazing story and one which taught me a little bit more about what it means to be human. I don't mean to make it sound pedantic -- there's plenty of plot and character development to keep you hooked from page one. There was only one part of the first book where I started to lose steam early on, and then it gets <i>really</i> interesting from there on out. <br />I will also add that I am not a big huge fan of sci-fi that creates too much new lingo and too many new characters, classes, races, etc. I think Lilith's Brood keeps a good balance of giving just enough of said newness to keep you intrigued and immersed without creating a need for a dictionary of terms and characters built into the back! </span>
  <a data-text-id="12537562497213832220" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


