<div id="review_8231033" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/8231033" />
    <a title="Jess" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21038-jess"><img alt="Jess" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1193332213p2/21038.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/8231033?book_show_action=true">Oct 25, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jess" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jess" href="/user/show/21038-jess">Jess</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">anyone</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21038-jess?shelf=best-evers">best-evers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer8231033" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17352462939073369272">I read <i>Dawn</i> a few months ago, and while I liked it, I wasn&apos;t blown away. After I read <i>Fledgling</i> and was newly impressed with Butler&apos;s creativity and way with language, I decided to finish the series. It absorbed me for two days, and I ended up absolutely loving it. This series reminded me of Vonnegut without the humor--where he uses absurdity to make a point, Butler lets that same point seep into you a little at a time. These books are about perception, violence, independence, and most of all, w</span>
  <span id="freeText17352462939073369272" style="display:none">I read <i>Dawn</i> a few months ago, and while I liked it, I wasn't blown away. After I read <i>Fledgling</i> and was newly impressed with Butler's creativity and way with language, I decided to finish the series. It absorbed me for two days, and I ended up absolutely loving it. This series reminded me of Vonnegut without the humor--where he uses absurdity to make a point, Butler lets that same point seep into you a little at a time. These books are about perception, violence, independence, and most of all, what it may take to make peace within humanity. Rather than choosing between utopia and dystopia, Butler writes a novel in which one cannot distinguish between the two. And that, my friends, is an interesting feat=)</span>
  <a data-text-id="17352462939073369272" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


