    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1126554363" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1126554363" />
    <a title="Craig" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4760634-craig"><img alt="Craig" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577908463p2/4760634.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1126554363?book_show_action=true">Dec 08, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Craig" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Craig" href="/user/show/4760634-craig">Craig</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Library Binding 9781439501696" href="/book/show/9650332-lilith-s-brood">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4760634-craig?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1126554363&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1126554363" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10680242584065320625">&quot;You are horror and beauty in rare combination.&quot;<br/><br/>Claustrophobic and taut, Butler knows how to play out the psychological effects of the mundane as well as the fantastic. And just when you start to think, &quot;gee, these reactions are pretty tame,&quot; the real horrors start to be uncovered: genetic tampering, psychological edits/ rewrites, and slavery/ imprisonment, the real underpinning being &quot;Who will win this Space Race?&quot;<br/><br/>Look, Butler is not going to let the reader out of this conundrum with easy answe</span>
  <span id="freeText10680242584065320625" style="display:none">"You are horror and beauty in rare combination."<br /><br />Claustrophobic and taut, Butler knows how to play out the psychological effects of the mundane as well as the fantastic. And just when you start to think, "gee, these reactions are pretty tame," the real horrors start to be uncovered: genetic tampering, psychological edits/ rewrites, and slavery/ imprisonment, the real underpinning being "Who will win this Space Race?"<br /><br />Look, Butler is not going to let the reader out of this conundrum with easy answers: for example, I was very disturbed by Lilith's "no rape!" policy only applying to women. When she allows a man -- her partner -- to be raped (not "seduced") by the aliens (and this won't be the last time this happens either), I was immediately questioning her autonomy. Are they puppets of the aliens, or are they really agreeing to being treated like animals, simply to survive and get back to Earth? Even still, this rape left me more than a little rattled (and gender has no bearing on my rape aversion, fyi. Rape is rape, no matter the victim's gender). And perhaps that's what Butler wants her male readers to feel so that they have a better sense of what rape is. But the notion that Lilith convinces herself that Joseph is enjoying it is incredibly disturbing, especially when he repeatedly says "no".<br /><br />In the second book, Akin, Lilith's son, becomes the potential savior of humanity. I expected more here, I have to confess, because the possibilities for resolution seemed very clear to me: Akin could simply merge with the other ooloi and steal the secret for unlocking human reproduction or infecting them with his own humanity to plant the seed for showing why humans need to be free, putting him in the position of being a traitor to his own people (echoing the story of Lilith in the first book). But we didn't get that. It's a lot of talking and made-up alien words (which I just skimmed over) and humans killing other humans. Damn, if Butler isn't a fatalist. It makes you wonder what happened to her in life that her view of humanity is so dark. Not that I disagree with her, for the most part, but it can get more than a little tedious reading lectures from the aliens about how we suck.<br /><br />The last book drags and drones.<br /><br />-1 star for rapey-ness and for a really bad romance novel/ mammogram brochure cover</span>
  <a data-text-id="10680242584065320625" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


