        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3714986121" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17055705098545760566">While I think Dawn, the first book in the series, is extremely powerful, making you question right and wrong, especially concerning the matter of consent, the other two captivated me less.<br/>Being introduced to the concepts in Dawn is fascinating and it was so easy to feel for Lilith. I would say it is very concept driven with a strong focus on relationships as well.<br/>The other two are more like journeys of self-discovery. You still learn more about the aliens and how the humans cope, but with the fo</span>
  <span id="freeText17055705098545760566" style="display:none">While I think Dawn, the first book in the series, is extremely powerful, making you question right and wrong, especially concerning the matter of consent, the other two captivated me less.<br />Being introduced to the concepts in Dawn is fascinating and it was so easy to feel for Lilith. I would say it is very concept driven with a strong focus on relationships as well.<br />The other two are more like journeys of self-discovery. You still learn more about the aliens and how the humans cope, but with the focus on how maturing children get to know humans and face predudices they were not able to intruige me in the same way. They also felt a bit repetitive, in themselves but also reading them back to back.<br />All of the novels are very strong concerning their themes, though, and enjoyable while still making you feel a bit uncomfortable. Like in all of Butler's books, gender, relationships, race and freedom are explored in unique way and there is a fascinating mix of bleakness and hope.</span>
