    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2753437468" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2753437468" />
    <a title="Jo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23043313-jo"><img alt="Jo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1555585027p2/23043313.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2753437468?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jo" href="/user/show/23043313-jo">Jo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23043313-jo?shelf=borrowed">borrowed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23043313-jo?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23043313-jo?shelf=read-in-2020">read-in-2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2753437468" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1776825765790950272">⭐ The Oankali are without a doubt in my top five aliens. They are superfluously Other; I was impressed throughout the trilogy by how sinister and inhuman Butler made them. She does that in many different ways, too - books two and three expand greatly on Oankali abilities, history and motivations and I was just constantly disturbed and delighted by how utterly weird they are.<br/><br/>⭐ It&apos;s the most subtle and thought-provoking depiction of Colonialism I&apos;ve yet come across in science fiction, and I think </span>
  <span id="freeText1776825765790950272" style="display:none">⭐ The Oankali are without a doubt in my top five aliens. They are superfluously Other; I was impressed throughout the trilogy by how sinister and inhuman Butler made them. She does that in many different ways, too - books two and three expand greatly on Oankali abilities, history and motivations and I was just constantly disturbed and delighted by how utterly weird they are.<br /><br />⭐ It's the most subtle and thought-provoking depiction of Colonialism I've yet come across in science fiction, and I think it moves way beyond that in books two and three. It made me question pretty much every moral I have, and gave no clear answers. That kind of self-interrogation is tiring but worthwhile; I rarely mull over/talk endlessly about books the way I did these three. I made notes. It was wild.<br /><br />⭐ Butler writes in a completely compelling way - eventually. I really disliked Dawn the first time I read it; slogged through it, even, but didn't stop thinking about it and went so far as to inflict it on others so I could talk to them about it (apologies again to the #bukekhleb folks). This time, I still didn't like Dawn, but I carried on a few pages into the second book and then I could not stop. Somehow, Butler made this trilogy so cohesive that I don't hate the first book so much anymore; it feels necessary to the whole.<br /><br />⭐ Just going to reiterate that the Oankali are really, really good aliens. They only get stranger as the trilogy goes on and I was horrified and delighted by them in basically equal measure. They're also villains who consider themselves saviours; that isn't done this well in anything else I've read.<br /><br />The downers:<br /><br />You do have to get through Dawn to get to the amazing parts. It isn't especially indicative of the other two.<br /><br />It's another one of those post-apocalyptic settings where apparently only arseholes survived; all of the humans are terrible in some way and most of them are REALLY terrible. Mind you, this pandemic is making me ever more of a misanthrope, so perhaps I've been too easy on Humanity and actually this trope has it right.<br /><br />There are only heterosexual, cis humans. This feels like a massive oversight and I was very disappointed by it.<br /><br />The biggest thing, for me: the pervasive sexualisation of children, by humans and by Oankali. I understand that this is an effective way to upset people and make monsters but it's so insidiously, quietly done; difficult to discuss without spoilers but it comes up in Fledgling as well and I just don't like it.<br /><br />This trilogy, taken as a whole, is incredible, but I didn't enjoy it in the traditional sense. And I'll never be able to look at sea anemones without cringing again. I'd still recommend it - read it and then come talk to me 😉<br /><br />Tl;dr: thought-and-discussion provoking; the aliens are awesome but everyone is awful.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1776825765790950272" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


